If you look at your nxn matrix there is a certain pattern to recognise. 

       1    2    5   10   17 
       4    3    6   11   18 
       9    8    7   12   19 
      16   15   14   13   20 
      25   24   23   22   21 

 - In the first column there are always square numbers
 - In the first row starting from the smallest square number 1 you are adding the sequence of odd numbers, i.e. `1,3,5,7,9,11 ....`

The patern for each row 

    [1]  +1 +3 +5 +7 ....
    [4]  -1 +3 +5 +7 ....
    [9]  -1 -1 +5 +7 ....
    [16] -1 -1 -1 +7 ....
    [25] -1 -1 -1 -1 ....
   
With this knowledge it is now easy to fill an `n x n` matrix. Create a list with the odd numbers from `1` to `columns-1`, fill the first row by adding the elements of your list one after the other, after each iteration replace the ith number in the list with `-1` to be able to use the list for the `i+1th` row.

Now for a non-square matrix, you can use the above approach to fill the square area of the matrix and handle the remaining rows or columns separately. Finding the size of the square area in order to difine a counter for the rest of rows/columns is relative simple. 

Just calculate `Math.pow(Math.min(rows, columns), 2);` 

I&#39;ve adopted your method names and changed your print method a bit. I did not comment the code, but hope it is clear what is being done. If anything is unclear do not hesitate to ask.

    import java.util.List;
    import java.util.stream.Collectors;
    import java.util.stream.IntStream;

    public class Test{

        public static int matrix[][];

        public static void main(String[] args) {
            borderLayout(5, 5);
            print();
        }

        public static void borderLayout(int rows, int columns) {
            //create a list (1,3,5, ...) with size = columns - 1
            List&lt;Integer&gt; list = IntStream.iterate(1, i -&gt; i + 2)
                    .limit(columns - 1).boxed()
                    .collect(Collectors.toList());
            matrix = new int[rows][columns];
            int square = Math.min(rows, columns);
            for (int i = 0; i &lt; square; i++) {
                int temp = (i + 1) * (i + 1);
                for (int j = 0; j &lt; square; j++) {
                    if (j == 0) {
                        matrix[i][j] = temp;
                    } else {
                        matrix[i][j] = matrix[i][j - 1] + list.get(j - 1);
                    }
                }
                if (i &lt; columns - 1) {
                    list.set(i, -1);
                }
            }
            if (rows &gt; columns) {
                int counter = (int) Math.pow(Math.min(rows, columns), 2);
                int sqrt = (int) Math.sqrt(counter);
                for (int i = sqrt; i &lt; rows; i++) {
                    for (int j = 0; j &lt; columns; j++) {
                        matrix[i][j] = ++counter;
                    }
                }
            } else if (rows &lt; columns) {
                int counter = (int) Math.pow(Math.min(rows, columns), 2);
                int sqrt = (int) Math.sqrt(counter);
                for (int i = sqrt; i &lt; columns; i++) {
                    for (int j = 0; j &lt; rows; j++) {
                        matrix[j][i] = ++counter;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

